00:03:59.290 --> 00:04:01.780
All right, well, you know what?

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:05.660
I think I want to start this conversation off here

00:04:06.499 --> 00:04:08.800
by talking about some of the articles you've written.

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:12.080
So I think this one's interesting.

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:16.500
Let's talk about virtual environments, okay?

00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:16.880
- Yeah.

00:04:18.019 --> 00:04:18.120
- Yeah?

00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:19.640
I think-- - Love them.

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:20.959
- I do too.

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:24.620
You wrote this article called

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:28.240
Why I Still Use Python Virtual Environments in Docker.

00:04:28.780 --> 00:04:29.880
And I do as well.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:32.760
And when I didn't use Docker,

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:34.640
I had them on my server as well.

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:39.080
And I feel like they're a really interesting,

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:42.680
predictable way to package Python.

00:04:42.860 --> 00:04:44.300
And you hear about them, obviously,

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:46.860
oh, well, you're going to create a virtual environment

00:04:47.180 --> 00:04:48.840
so you can have multiple projects

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:50.400
in your computer and so on.

00:04:51.020 --> 00:04:53.380
But Docker, there's only one app running.

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:55.160
What's the deal with these virtual environments in Docker?

00:04:56.780 --> 00:04:58.760
Yeah, I mean, you just said it, right?

00:04:58.860 --> 00:05:01.400
It's a lot more predictable in its behavior.

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:04.160
It's a technology that we use everywhere too.

00:05:05.160 --> 00:05:08.740
And I just understand what this directory is doing, right?

00:05:09.740 --> 00:05:20.020
And I find it very important that when I just go on a server or in a Docker container, I know what a file is doing or how things interact with each other.

00:05:20.190 --> 00:05:22.440
And I don't have to hunt them down somewhere else.

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:30.900
Or another popular thing is that I write in the first paragraph is that people use pipinstore user and then set the Python user base directory.

00:05:31.700 --> 00:05:33.140
And sure, you can do all these things.

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:36.300
But why would you, right?

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:37.840
Like, what are you gaining?

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:42.600
and it's a lot of vibes

00:05:42.670 --> 00:05:44.380
and I admit it in the article too

00:05:44.680 --> 00:05:46.400
but I just find it easier to reason about

00:05:46.950 --> 00:05:47.620
and not everything

00:05:48.410 --> 00:05:50.180
we don't use only things we need

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:52.880
we use affordances in other places too

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:54.100
so why not this

00:05:54.430 --> 00:05:55.560
as an abstraction over

00:05:56.570 --> 00:05:57.520
an application artifact

00:05:57.840 --> 00:05:59.160
because we don't have anything better in Python

00:06:01.639 --> 00:06:03.620
yeah and also one of the things

00:06:04.060 --> 00:06:05.220
that you point out in your article

00:06:05.360 --> 00:06:06.359
that I think is really nice

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:10.320
that's already the way you're working on your computer.

00:06:11.960 --> 00:06:14.620
And so when you go to your Docker container,

00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:16.520
it's the same.

00:06:17.070 --> 00:06:17.860
You don't have to think about,

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:20.500
well, if it's misbehaving in production,

00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:24.480
that's because, well, maybe we've changed the Python path

00:06:24.490 --> 00:06:26.280
or whatever, right?

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:29.260
It's exactly the same as everyone else is working with.

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:31.500
Yeah, we forgot to set an environment variable.

00:06:31.590 --> 00:06:33.000
Oh no, nothing works now.

00:06:34.420 --> 00:06:34.740
Exactly.

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:39.100
Oh, boy, that's been interesting.

00:06:39.470 --> 00:06:42.300
So, you know, what's your...

00:06:43.460 --> 00:06:45.900
Let's talk about Docker just a little bit as well.

00:06:45.950 --> 00:06:50.340
I think that alone is a pretty interesting choice.

00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:54.680
You said you work on smaller teams

00:06:55.150 --> 00:06:57.420
and maybe web hosting companies

00:06:57.890 --> 00:07:03.600
give this a little bit of a plus-plus slant on Docker or not.

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:07.720
But Docker, no Docker, a lot of people, I think,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:09.620
see containers and they think complexity.

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:11.440
They think it's hard to debug.

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:14.760
If something goes wrong in the container, it's opaque to me.

00:07:16.780 --> 00:07:20.200
What would you say to people that feel like containers are too complicated?

00:07:23.240 --> 00:07:25.100
Obviously, the answer is, as always, it depends.

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:27.860
It's a trade-off like everything else.

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:32.560
We don't give Docker to our customers.

00:07:32.800 --> 00:07:34.780
like our customer, we sell mostly LAMP,

00:07:34.890 --> 00:07:37.600
like mostly WordPress, which is very interesting these days.

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:39.460
- Oh my gosh.

00:07:39.740 --> 00:07:41.120
I don't know if we want to go down that one,

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:44.000
but it is super, super turmoil right now.

00:07:44.150 --> 00:07:44.360
- Yeah, yeah.

00:07:44.420 --> 00:07:44.980
- No, we don't.

00:07:45.080 --> 00:07:45.680
Let's talk about it.

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:47.700
- Matt doesn't know we exist.

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:48.080
It's fine.

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:54.400
Yeah, so you're trading off the things you just said,

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:56.320
like the debuggability and everything

00:07:58.020 --> 00:08:01.560
against development of velocity and reproducibility.

00:08:03.160 --> 00:08:05.400
So we, for example, we don't run Kubernetes

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:08.100
because it's just too complex for us to run

00:08:08.290 --> 00:08:09.760
and we run everything on premise.

00:08:10.020 --> 00:08:11.360
So like we do not have anything,

00:08:11.810 --> 00:08:13.880
we do not use any external services whatsoever.

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:15.100
- Wow, okay.

00:08:15.740 --> 00:08:18.100
- Right, so everything runs into our own data centers.

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:21.280
So we are Europeans, some of the things we do,

00:08:21.530 --> 00:08:23.740
other things we do because Germans like it that way.

00:08:23.740 --> 00:08:28.440
We can say like our data center is right there.

00:08:28.510 --> 00:08:30.860
You can look at it, no data leaves it.

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:36.440
Yeah, if you have to, I can come look at my code through the little rack window.

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:37.419
There it is.

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:40.820
You can try around inside and see how fast you get tasered by the security side.

00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:41.840
It's all good.

00:08:44.140 --> 00:08:47.460
But we use quite a bit of HashiCorp software.

00:08:47.570 --> 00:08:53.000
So we had Consul and Vault before for configuration, service discovery, and secrets.

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:58.940
So we use Nomad because it was a logical add-on to run our applications.

00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:02.680
So that's where most of our web applications run.

00:09:02.900 --> 00:09:04.680
Everything that can run in containers

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:09.280
usually runs in our Nomad cluster in Docker containers.

00:09:11.540 --> 00:09:15.360
And yeah, sometimes there are a bit of a pain to debug.

00:09:15.580 --> 00:09:18.160
But you can SSH into a Docker container, right?

00:09:18.390 --> 00:09:19.820
So yeah.

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:24.720
And first hot tip of the day, there's

00:09:24.730 --> 00:09:27.580
this thing called BusyBox, which is like one command.

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:29.540
And depending on what name you call it,

00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:30.220
something different.

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:35.820
And it's just very few bytes.

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:37.260
You can look at it.

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:38.440
And it's static.

00:09:38.740 --> 00:09:41.360
And it gives me things like ping.

00:09:41.920 --> 00:09:44.600
And I think traceroute is in there, too.

00:09:45.670 --> 00:09:49.880
So I can do all these basic things in those containers, too.

00:09:49.930 --> 00:09:51.980
So it's not like it's a completely black box.

00:09:52.010 --> 00:09:53.060
You can SSH into them.

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:53.680
It's no problem.

00:09:56.890 --> 00:09:57.980
A couple of thoughts.

00:09:58.320 --> 00:09:59.720
One, I agree with you on--

00:09:59.720 --> 00:09:59.840
One more thing.

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:00.220
One more thing.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:00.780
Yeah, yeah, go ahead.

00:10:01.290 --> 00:10:01.460
Yeah, yeah.

00:10:02.260 --> 00:10:05.280
We do not run SSH clients on those Docker containers.

00:10:05.540 --> 00:10:08.480
So this is an affordance that we get from Nomad,

00:10:08.490 --> 00:10:11.480
and I'm sure other cluster managers have that too,

00:10:11.700 --> 00:10:15.220
that they allow you to enter containers from the outside.

00:10:15.410 --> 00:10:18.360
So you SSH into the host, and from there,

00:10:18.390 --> 00:10:19.300
you get into the container.

00:10:19.660 --> 00:10:19.800
Right.

00:10:20.200 --> 00:10:22.180
There's no SSH service.

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:26.220
Yeah, I do that as well on my stuff.

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:30.860
I've recently moved a couple, maybe a year or two ago,

00:10:31.180 --> 00:10:34.000
to running, I used to have a bunch of smaller servers.

00:10:34.940 --> 00:10:37.920
I don't know, maybe I bought into the cloud computing

00:10:38.110 --> 00:10:39.640
as a bunch of commodity boxes,

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:41.420
and you can just make a bunch of little ones,

00:10:41.490 --> 00:10:42.560
and that's the way you do it.

00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:44.600
And eventually I'm just like, you know what?

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.140
I'm tired of dealing with all these servers.

00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:50.240
Putting them all in one thing, running everything in Docker,

00:10:50.520 --> 00:10:51.140
keeping it isolated.

00:10:51.270 --> 00:10:55.320
And it's been really excellent, so a similar access model there.

00:10:58.920 --> 00:11:06.260
i'm not sure this makes sense for you guys but i think for folks who maybe expected still to ssh

00:11:06.360 --> 00:11:10.380
into their server and and mess with it you know maybe this doesn't make sense for your customers

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:14.660
but maybe it does for you guys individually behind the scenes is

00:11:17.040 --> 00:11:20.999
i like to have a couple of tools a little bit like you were saying busybox

00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:23.520
already installed in my Docker container.

00:11:23.650 --> 00:11:26.700
So if I need to get into it and ask it questions,

00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:33.180
I can actually log in through some sort of Docker exec,

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:37.720
Docker exec, dash IT, sort of ZSH or bash or whatever,

00:11:38.720 --> 00:11:40.100
and ask it questions.

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:41.100
What are your thoughts?

00:11:41.130 --> 00:11:42.840
Do you think if you put something like,

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:44.760
oh, my Z shell, so you have better command history

00:11:44.910 --> 00:11:46.300
while you're poking around,

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:49.820
is that sacrilegious in a Docker container?

00:11:50.100 --> 00:11:51.240
How do you feel about this?

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:53.600
You're asking me if you have a fancy...

00:11:53.810 --> 00:11:55.820
Well, we are sacrilegious in a different way.

00:11:55.940 --> 00:11:57.940
Like our normal servers that we SSH into,

00:11:58.340 --> 00:12:00.460
we run phish on them because most of us like phish.

00:12:00.980 --> 00:12:01.340
Yeah, sure.

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:04.660
So we have very nice phish prompts running there

00:12:04.940 --> 00:12:08.540
and everybody who claims they have to use Bash on their notebooks

00:12:08.820 --> 00:12:10.560
because they have to SSH into servers,

00:12:10.940 --> 00:12:11.620
look at us.

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:12.380
It's fine.

00:12:12.670 --> 00:12:13.680
You can do whatever you want.

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:14.720
It's your servers, man.

00:12:16.460 --> 00:12:16.880
I'm with you.

00:12:17.380 --> 00:12:18.979
I don't have this strong opinions

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:20.980
because, as I said, we run everything on-prem,

00:12:21.080 --> 00:12:22.380
so we have our own Docker registry,

00:12:22.720 --> 00:12:26.020
so I'm not losing sleep over how big my containers are.

00:12:27.040 --> 00:12:30.000
Obviously, I try to keep the surface small

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:33.820
because everything you install can probably be misused in some way,

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:37.140
can be a problem like XZ, for example.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:40.480
Things can be dangerous,

00:12:40.740 --> 00:12:44.120
but if it helps you to get things done, whatever.

00:12:44.920 --> 00:12:50.680
Yeah, when you hear the security folks talk about living off the land,

00:12:51.080 --> 00:12:51.640
that's what they mean.

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:54.500
They're like, oh, I somehow got into this machine,

00:12:54.740 --> 00:12:59.140
and it turns out that this tool that I needed to access the database

00:12:59.270 --> 00:13:01.700
was just laying here, and off it goes, right?

00:13:01.820 --> 00:13:03.420
They didn't have to get anything on the server.

00:13:04.640 --> 00:13:06.760
So that, in a sense, you kind of want to eliminate.

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:11.900
I do think the tradeoff is, are you pushing to a Docker registry

00:13:12.130 --> 00:13:13.760
and shipping the thing all around,

00:13:13.920 --> 00:13:18.260
or is it just being built in some local-ish story, right?

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:21.340
Interesting.

00:13:21.620 --> 00:13:21.800
Okay.

00:13:24.079 --> 00:13:28.100
So the reason that I found out about your article,

00:13:28.960 --> 00:13:33.340
your virtual environment article,

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:38.880
is I was actually looking around at your uv article

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:43.140
because, wow, does uv speed up Docker builds?

00:13:43.800 --> 00:13:44.920
Oh yeah, oh yeah.

00:13:48.380 --> 00:13:50.420
So Jay Miller made a comment just yesterday I saw that,

00:13:51.070 --> 00:13:53.440
it was pretty funny, he said uv is the new AI,

00:13:54.290 --> 00:13:56.400
and I suppose AI is the new blockchain.

00:13:57.240 --> 00:13:58.400
Everyone's excited about it,

00:13:58.860 --> 00:14:02.900
there's some minor level of controversy about it,

00:14:03.460 --> 00:14:05.180
but I don't know, I'm a big fan.

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:06.800
What are your thoughts on uv these days?

00:14:07.380 --> 00:14:08.860
First of all, for people who don't know,

00:14:09.880 --> 00:14:11.840
we're talking a lot of two letter acronym,

00:14:11.860 --> 00:14:13.380
