00:36:08.440 --> 00:36:09.520
that we are not thinking about.

00:36:09.610 --> 00:36:11.340
Because a lot of the arguments against it

00:36:11.480 --> 00:36:14.340
was, oh, threads are bad.

00:36:14.460 --> 00:36:16.820
It's hard to write multi-threaded code, which is all true.

00:36:17.880 --> 00:36:20.300
The problem is that we just don't have good APIs for that.

00:36:20.540 --> 00:36:22.580
You can build good APIs for threading.

00:36:23.420 --> 00:36:25.220
You just have to look what Go is doing with channels.

00:36:25.460 --> 00:36:29.040
We can have channels in Python once we have good threading.

00:36:29.940 --> 00:36:33.300
But we never bothered to build these kind of APIs

00:36:33.470 --> 00:36:35.300
because it doesn't make any sense with the guild.

00:36:36.340 --> 00:36:37.540
It's better to go async.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:39.720
That's a really good point.

00:36:40.180 --> 00:36:42.220
And I think there's an analogy with async.

00:36:43.470 --> 00:36:46.140
Remember, async.io shipped in Python 3.4,

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:49.080
but async await, the keywords in the programming model

00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:49.840
shipped in 3.5.

00:36:50.200 --> 00:36:53.700
So for a while, it was like, well, you guys figured it out.

00:36:54.040 --> 00:36:55.780
And then the programming model got way nicer.

00:36:56.300 --> 00:36:56.700
Yeah.

00:36:57.620 --> 00:37:01.020
Yeah, I think we might have not gotten this shot

00:37:01.220 --> 00:37:03.260
if AsyncIO didn't happen back then,

00:37:03.400 --> 00:37:07.260
because it just showed how we can do a test balloon

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:08.060
in a community.

00:37:10.640 --> 00:37:14.940
And we don't have to do it perfectly on the first time.

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:19.700
I think we had even breaking changes in minor releases of 3.5

00:37:20.680 --> 00:37:22.720
because we had to fix things up.

00:37:23.060 --> 00:37:26.340
So yeah, I'm sure it was a bit of an inspiration.

00:37:27.079 --> 00:37:30.620
I remember a breaking change somewhere in Python,

00:37:30.840 --> 00:37:34.960
but further down the road where the async context,

00:37:36.580 --> 00:37:39.020
so the way to say a function was async,

00:37:39.100 --> 00:37:41.960
you could use a decorator before async and await came along.

00:37:43.519 --> 00:37:46.540
And my code, which was running on MongoDB,

00:37:46.720 --> 00:37:49.100
which was using motor,

00:37:50.020 --> 00:37:53.300
They were using that older style to get their async.

00:37:53.760 --> 00:37:55.160
And then when it got taken out of Python,

00:37:55.280 --> 00:37:57.760
it just, well, stuff doesn't run anymore.

00:37:58.400 --> 00:38:00.820
There is no such decorator async,

00:38:00.900 --> 00:38:02.380
something I can't remember exactly what it was.

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:06.540
But it took a week or two before I could run the new Python

00:38:06.720 --> 00:38:07.960
because that wasn't a big deal.

00:38:08.280 --> 00:38:09.860
I just didn't use it.

00:38:09.880 --> 00:38:11.140
But it did break things.

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:14.020
There was plenty of breaking changes in async.io

00:38:14.460 --> 00:38:17.120
because I was quite involved with that whole thing.

00:38:17.320 --> 00:38:19.720
And I remember things breaking a lot in the beginning.

00:38:20.260 --> 00:38:24.960
But it's good that we don't carry that technical debt around with us now.

00:38:25.520 --> 00:38:26.780
Yeah, absolutely.

00:38:27.320 --> 00:38:35.360
I want to give a quick shout out to a pytest plugin called pytest-FreeThreaded from Anthony Shaw and friends.

00:38:35.880 --> 00:38:47.740
And this one basically lets you run your tests in the free-threaded Python mode and run them with parallelism and stuff like that.

00:38:48.360 --> 00:38:50.980
Because if you're going to have a library and you have tests for it

00:38:51.320 --> 00:38:52.980
and it's supposed to support free threading,

00:38:53.660 --> 00:38:56.720
you should probably test it with free threading actually running at some point, right?

00:38:59.620 --> 00:39:03.420
So anyway, people are trying to move their libraries along.

00:39:04.540 --> 00:39:07.220
I think they said, look, we tested this on one of the libraries

00:39:07.460 --> 00:39:11.980
that said it was free threaded supporting it, segfaulted Python.

00:39:12.520 --> 00:39:15.040
So maybe it wasn't quite ready.

00:39:15.100 --> 00:39:17.960
So run your tests if you're going to support this.

00:39:18.780 --> 00:39:23.440
I think it needs to be stressed that the trick to not break your code

00:39:23.480 --> 00:39:27.060
is to just not mutate global data in multiple threads at once.

00:39:30.279 --> 00:39:33.500
It's just avoid doing this and you'll be fine.

00:39:33.640 --> 00:39:34.740
And most people don't.

00:39:34.900 --> 00:39:37.380
So I don't expect like this large scale breakage.

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:41.480
The problem is more in the lower level things like CFFI

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:45.040
and those kind of things that are going to take a lot of time

00:39:45.060 --> 00:39:45.440
I think.

00:39:45.920 --> 00:39:46.940
Yeah, I agree.

