00:48:45.500 --> 00:48:48.080
Let's talk a little bit about some of your projects.

00:48:48.660 --> 00:48:49.740
You talked about Argon.

00:48:50.880 --> 00:48:53.660
I think maybe one of the things you're best known for

00:48:53.720 --> 00:48:55.240
might be Adders, would you say?

00:48:55.980 --> 00:48:56.280
What do you think?

00:48:56.680 --> 00:48:58.340
It depends who you ask.

00:48:59.600 --> 00:49:03.100
I think Adders had the biggest impact on the community

00:49:03.320 --> 00:49:05.720
because they are the direct predecessor of data classes

00:49:06.040 --> 00:49:09.560
that I designed with Guido and Eric back then.

00:49:10.340 --> 00:49:12.300
That goes back to Adders because people

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:14.940
wanted something like Adders in a standard library.

00:49:15.660 --> 00:49:16.860
But yeah.

00:49:17.310 --> 00:49:19.220
JOHN MUELLER: Tell people about Adders,

00:49:19.470 --> 00:49:20.220
for those who don't know.

00:49:24.100 --> 00:49:24.200
Yeah.

00:49:24.430 --> 00:49:27.900
I mean, imagine data classes, but more powerful.

00:49:29.040 --> 00:49:32.260
People sometimes try to compare it to Pydantic,

00:49:32.620 --> 00:49:34.600
but that's not that.

00:49:35.500 --> 00:49:37.960
Adders is not trying to be a validation thing.

00:49:38.640 --> 00:49:42.280
Adders is there for creating classes

00:49:42.300 --> 00:49:42.720
written yourself.

00:49:44.200 --> 00:49:46.940
I call it a class writing toolkit.

00:49:48.800 --> 00:49:51.240
And data classes keep catching up with what we do,

00:49:51.370 --> 00:49:52.320
but we are still ahead.

00:49:52.390 --> 00:49:53.520
So we have more features.

00:49:54.090 --> 00:49:54.700
We work better.

00:49:55.060 --> 00:49:58.700
And especially for data science-y things,

00:49:58.980 --> 00:50:02.980
because we allow people to define comparisons in a custom way.

00:50:02.990 --> 00:50:05.920
So you can compare NumPy arrays and everything.

00:50:07.200 --> 00:50:11.100
And you don't need to use type annotations if you hate them.

00:50:11.300 --> 00:50:12.620
That's also a big feature we have.

00:50:13.840 --> 00:50:14.720
Okay, interesting.

00:50:15.310 --> 00:50:17.740
Yeah, so when you create a class,

00:50:18.430 --> 00:50:20.260
you can just put some fields on it, and that's great.

00:50:21.380 --> 00:50:24.240
But there's probably some other things you might want to do,

00:50:24.560 --> 00:50:27.700
like to find a hash and to find an equals and a not equals

00:50:28.600 --> 00:50:33.340
and a stir and a repper and all these kinds of things, right?

00:50:34.180 --> 00:50:34.320
Yeah.

00:50:34.560 --> 00:50:37.140
And you just get that out of the box, right?

00:50:37.760 --> 00:50:39.760
And maybe you want the class to be frozen.

00:50:40.260 --> 00:50:42.760
Maybe you want slots and these kind of things.

00:50:43.410 --> 00:50:45.080
MARK BLYTH: Slots, interesting.

00:50:45.830 --> 00:50:46.280
I don't know.

00:50:46.380 --> 00:50:47.280
Everyone knows about slots.

00:50:47.380 --> 00:50:53.640
Slots are kind of a cheat code for low memory, fast access.

00:50:54.470 --> 00:50:55.860
Tell people about slots, dunder slots.

00:50:56.670 --> 00:50:59.180
FRANCESC CAMPOY: Well, when you create a class in Python,

00:50:59.560 --> 00:51:01.660
by default, it's a so-called dictionary class

00:51:01.980 --> 00:51:06.480
because it has a dunder dict field where all the attributes

00:51:06.650 --> 00:51:07.180
are defined.

00:51:07.940 --> 00:51:09.720
And you can do with those classes whatever you want.

00:51:09.840 --> 00:51:10.900
You can just add more attributes.

00:51:11.840 --> 00:51:14.260
But if you define a slotted class, which

00:51:14.680 --> 00:51:17.160
doesn't have this dunderdict but dunder slots,

00:51:17.580 --> 00:51:21.080
and you enumerate all attributes that this class will have,

00:51:21.200 --> 00:51:22.500
and it's then baked into the class.

00:51:23.500 --> 00:51:24.760
So this has the big upside.

00:51:25.160 --> 00:51:28.640
If you try to assign an attribute that doesn't exist,

00:51:29.300 --> 00:51:32.480
it will throw an error, which is good because it probably

00:51:32.680 --> 00:51:33.760
means that you mistyped.

00:51:34.480 --> 00:51:36.540
And this is like the thing that you see from the outside.

00:51:36.780 --> 00:51:38.080
From the inside, it's much more interesting

00:51:38.260 --> 00:51:39.800
because those classes are more baked

00:51:40.520 --> 00:51:41.260
So they are just faster.

00:51:41.460 --> 00:51:42.900
They're faster and use less memory.

00:51:44.480 --> 00:51:45.860
Yeah, they use quite a bit.

00:51:46.110 --> 00:51:49.240
I think named tuples use more memory, you know,

00:51:49.240 --> 00:51:53.780
and you think how tuples kind of like as about as bare bones as it can get.

00:51:54.400 --> 00:51:56.400
But yeah, it's quite interesting.

00:51:56.490 --> 00:52:01.400
And my experience is that even attribute access is a tiny bit faster

00:52:02.840 --> 00:52:03.740
than in regular classes.

00:52:04.460 --> 00:52:07.500
Yeah, and this is why in the new APIs, it's the default in others.

00:52:09.580 --> 00:52:13.040
Like data classes grew slots too, but it's optional in others.

00:52:13.240 --> 00:52:16.760
It's now opt out because it's really good.

00:52:16.760 --> 00:52:17.080
Oh, it is.

00:52:17.460 --> 00:52:19.220
Yeah, yeah, because why not?

00:52:19.380 --> 00:52:25.140
And my experience is it's cool to have the dynamic nature of classes and types

00:52:25.240 --> 00:52:27.540
and you can do all sorts of stuff to change them,

00:52:28.140 --> 00:52:29.200
but most of the time you don't.

00:52:30.020 --> 00:52:32.140
And if you're not going to, like you said,

00:52:32.220 --> 00:52:37.140
get the I mistyped something catch because they won't let you do it

00:52:37.500 --> 00:52:39.660
and the better memory and better performance, right?

00:52:40.020 --> 00:52:43.680
Yeah, I think this is something that Rust has changed too.

00:52:44.480 --> 00:52:45.800
The influence of Rust on Python

00:52:45.870 --> 00:52:48.580
has been that we got a little less dynamic with time,

00:52:48.940 --> 00:52:50.340
which I personally think is a good thing

00:52:50.430 --> 00:52:53.000
because I started moving away from that sooner.

00:52:54.380 --> 00:52:56.700
Using dictionaries and tuples and all these things,

00:52:57.960 --> 00:52:59.840
it's just very hard to reason about

00:52:59.950 --> 00:53:01.300
when you come back a year later

00:53:01.310 --> 00:53:03.040
and try to understand what this code is doing.

00:53:04.020 --> 00:53:05.160
Yeah, yeah.

00:53:05.980 --> 00:53:08.840
What is this *star kwhargs thing? What are we doing here?

00:53:09.800 --> 00:53:18.540
There's still so many APIs. You have a nice IDE, you press F12, you jump to the function and it's *star quarks.

00:53:19.220 --> 00:53:19.540
Thank you.

00:53:20.300 --> 00:53:29.840
Yes, exactly. You know, if that works out well, there might be a big doc string that says these are the seven things that can actually go in these keyword arguments and here's their type.

00:53:29.840 --> 00:53:31.620
And if you're extra lucky, it's true.

00:53:34.440 --> 00:53:37.920
Yeah, it's actually true or it's actually comprehensive.

00:53:38.880 --> 00:53:39.940
Yeah, I don't know.

00:53:39.980 --> 00:53:43.220
I feel a lot of times when you're doing that kind of stuff,

00:53:43.340 --> 00:53:44.780
if you end up back in the documentation,

00:53:45.460 --> 00:53:46.900
like something's kind of gone a little bit wrong,

00:53:47.160 --> 00:53:48.680
like you should probably be able to tell at least,

00:53:50.660 --> 00:53:51.840
does it take arguments?

00:53:52.380 --> 00:53:53.820
What might they possibly be?

00:53:54.360 --> 00:53:57.180
But then you go to the documentation, it's auto-generating.

00:53:57.280 --> 00:54:00.480
You're like, well, no, not getting far on this one.

00:54:01.600 --> 00:54:08.340
Well, since we have this, the Opinion of Hennig episode,

00:54:08.760 --> 00:54:09.760
what are your thoughts on types?

00:54:10.800 --> 00:54:11.260
What do you think?

00:54:11.540 --> 00:54:12.400
I love types.

00:54:14.180 --> 00:54:17.980
Like I just said, I was moving to more static things

00:54:18.140 --> 00:54:19.920
in general because it's just easier to reason about,

00:54:20.460 --> 00:54:21.360
easier to understand.

00:54:22.500 --> 00:54:24.540
And it informs the design of APIs, too,

00:54:24.680 --> 00:54:29.180
like which I just find the APIs that come out nowadays

00:54:29.200 --> 00:54:32.340
are widely more accessible than we used to have.

00:54:33.700 --> 00:54:37.240
And Lukasz Lange's keynote a few years ago at PyCon US

00:54:37.280 --> 00:54:38.880
was like, if something is hard to type,

00:54:38.980 --> 00:54:40.360
maybe it's just bad design.

00:54:41.040 --> 00:54:42.640
That's an interesting take, yeah.

00:54:42.860 --> 00:54:44.340
It's not always true, by the way.

00:54:44.480 --> 00:54:47.160
There are legitimate use cases for Python

00:54:47.480 --> 00:54:49.380
where typing is a bad fit.

00:54:49.940 --> 00:54:51.340
And it's completely true.

00:54:51.400 --> 00:54:52.660
And it's not great for everything.

00:54:53.240 --> 00:54:54.660
But I personally just take any help

00:54:54.720 --> 00:54:58.500
that I can get that helps me to make my code more

00:54:58.520 --> 00:55:05.600
understandable and help me ensure that I'm writing what I'm thinking I'm writing.

00:55:06.600 --> 00:55:13.860
Types help me the best with finding logic errors in what I thought I was passing around

00:55:13.980 --> 00:55:15.380
and what I was actually passing around.

00:55:15.560 --> 00:55:21.460
Because things that work by accident because something gets autoconverted somewhere are

00:55:21.460 --> 00:55:25.280
the most dangerous things because they explode when you are on the beach with your margarita.

00:55:26.760 --> 00:55:27.260
Yeah, they do.

00:55:27.260 --> 00:55:28.120
And that's not good.

00:55:28.300 --> 00:55:29.140
as we already pointed out.

00:55:30.110 --> 00:55:31.820
You know, another thing that I really like about them,

00:55:31.900 --> 00:55:35.460
I'm kind of on your team with this one as well,

00:55:35.550 --> 00:55:38.380
and I really like that, I hinted at that before,

00:55:38.520 --> 00:55:40.340
you don't have to go to the documentation and go like,

00:55:40.340 --> 00:55:40.980
what is this?

00:55:41.130 --> 00:55:43.060
I know it says it takes an options,

00:55:43.630 --> 00:55:44.520
but what is an options?

00:55:44.670 --> 00:55:46.300
You know, like I have no idea what goes here still.

00:55:46.500 --> 00:55:47.120
This doesn't tell me.

00:55:47.600 --> 00:55:49.580
But if it means it's this class or it's a dictionary,

00:55:49.710 --> 00:55:51.240
well, at least you got some hints on like,

00:55:51.240 --> 00:55:54.200
well, this is where I start knowing what I'm supposed to do here.

00:55:54.900 --> 00:55:56.400
And also with the editor, right?

00:55:56.500 --> 00:56:00.140
If I hit dot, it gives you a way better chance

00:56:00.270 --> 00:56:03.200
of just continuing to type instead of going and looking up stuff.

00:56:04.180 --> 00:56:07.420
And also, that's something people don't talk that much about.

00:56:07.580 --> 00:56:10.100
But it forces you to give things names.

00:56:10.900 --> 00:56:11.180
You know?

00:56:12.440 --> 00:56:17.140
And sometimes, when you have problems to give a type name,

00:56:17.400 --> 00:56:20.500
that's a sign that you don't quite understand what the thing is doing.

00:56:20.590 --> 00:56:21.880
Or maybe it's doing too many things.

00:56:22.360 --> 00:56:25.760
And that way, you have this instant feedback

00:56:25.780 --> 00:56:27.620
about your design and how you think about things.

00:56:28.220 --> 00:56:29.480
That I find very useful.

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:33.820
And also, I have to point is, if typing would be just

00:56:34.360 --> 00:56:36.220
marking things that could be none or not,

00:56:36.550 --> 00:56:40.400
that would be already like 99% of the value of types.

00:56:40.820 --> 00:56:45.900
Like just helping to avoid non-type errors.

00:56:45.960 --> 00:56:47.640
- Yeah, optional or not optional,

00:56:47.780 --> 00:56:48.500
what are we going to do here?

00:56:48.920 --> 00:56:49.220
- Yeah.

00:56:49.940 --> 00:56:52.640
- Yeah, I do like that it's optional,

00:56:52.980 --> 00:56:54.980
that it's progressive, right?

00:56:55.700 --> 00:56:59.500
I came from static languages to Python,

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:01.200
and the fact that it didn't have types,

00:57:01.290 --> 00:57:02.420
I kind of wanted something.

00:57:02.820 --> 00:57:04.840
But I also played around with TypeScript,

00:57:06.919 --> 00:57:08.960
and I've battled with the TypeScript system

00:57:09.220 --> 00:57:11.140
where it's like, well, we don't know what this thing is,

00:57:11.170 --> 00:57:12.440
but you're supposed to pass in something

00:57:12.620 --> 00:57:13.900
that's known in the type system.

00:57:15.070 --> 00:57:15.960
I know this will work.

00:57:16.170 --> 00:57:17.740
Just get out of my way and let me do it.

00:57:17.820 --> 00:57:18.320
You know what I mean?

00:57:20.390 --> 00:57:23.160
And I think there's a pretty good balance that's caught here.

00:57:23.900 --> 00:57:27.060
Yeah, I think, so I have a whole keynote in my head

00:57:27.180 --> 00:57:30.240
about the true Python superpower is the graduality.

00:57:30.800 --> 00:57:33.320
Because you can start with the biggest trash,

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:35.740
shitty code in a Jupyter notebook

00:57:36.760 --> 00:57:39.400
and just work yourself up by putting it in a file,

00:57:39.520 --> 00:57:42.900
running rough linter, then adding types, and so on.

00:57:42.900 --> 00:57:46.300
And you end up with production code of the best kind.

00:57:47.200 --> 00:57:48.640
But you started with complete shit.

00:57:48.710 --> 00:57:49.800
And that's how my brain works.

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:51.800
Like, I like to try things out

00:57:51.940 --> 00:57:53.920
and then just polish the turd, must I say.

00:57:54.780 --> 00:57:58.400
Polish it when it's proven that it's worth putting your time and energy to, right?

00:57:58.420 --> 00:58:01.040
And I find this very frustrating with languages like Rust or Go.

00:58:01.640 --> 00:58:06.300
I read a lot of Go, and Go won't even compile your thing if you have an unused import.

00:58:06.400 --> 00:58:07.900
And this is just so frustrating.

00:58:09.520 --> 00:58:10.300
Oh my gosh, okay.

00:58:10.340 --> 00:58:11.840
Just eat my trash and make it work.

00:58:11.980 --> 00:58:13.580
I will fix it later, I promise.

00:58:15.900 --> 00:58:17.060
That's a pretty interesting take.

00:58:18.180 --> 00:58:25.580
All right, well, let's give maybe a shout out to Stamina also.

00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:27.360
Like, that's--

00:58:27.820 --> 00:58:29.320
That was a surprise to me.

00:58:29.800 --> 00:58:30.240
Yeah?

00:58:31.760 --> 00:58:34.640
Yeah, it's like from my latest projects,

00:58:34.900 --> 00:58:37.800
kind of the most popular one, because it just

00:58:37.910 --> 00:58:40.540
solved the problem we all have, that we use Tenacity, which

00:58:40.620 --> 00:58:42.240
is a great--

00:58:43.720 --> 00:58:45.080
sorry, I muted myself for a second.

00:58:45.740 --> 00:58:47.780
We all used Tenacity, which is a great package,

00:58:48.940 --> 00:58:51.520
but it has no good default because it's also

00:58:51.620 --> 00:58:52.240
a very old package.

00:58:53.500 --> 00:58:57.180
And everybody's just copy-pasting these standard settings

00:58:57.660 --> 00:59:00.620
around that make it behave in a good way.

00:59:02.100 --> 00:59:04.580
And it's also, at least back then, didn't do proper typing.

00:59:05.240 --> 00:59:07.980
So I just wrote this tiny shim around that

00:59:08.000 --> 00:59:11.440
so I can stop copy-pasting the same things over and over again.

00:59:11.900 --> 00:59:13.740
It turns out a lot of people have the same problem.

00:59:15.120 --> 00:59:20.020
Yeah, so if you've got a function, for example,

00:59:20.160 --> 00:59:21.120
like a little example here,

00:59:21.780 --> 00:59:25.080
that might crash because an HTTP error.

00:59:26.600 --> 00:59:27.120
Like, you know what?

00:59:27.160 --> 00:59:29.940
If I just tried this again, I bet it would work, right?

00:59:30.160 --> 00:59:33.280
Just add stamina.retry, specify the error.

00:59:35.480 --> 00:59:36.800
It's been a while since I checked it out,

00:59:36.800 --> 00:59:40.540
but it's got exponential backoff and other things like that.

00:59:41.820 --> 00:59:42.900
Oh, and jitter, okay, nice.

00:59:44.480 --> 00:59:44.880
Yeah.

00:59:45.660 --> 00:59:47.500
I use it in certain things.

00:59:48.180 --> 00:59:50.020
It's not very often that you need something like this,

00:59:50.080 --> 00:59:52.120
but when you do, you're like, oh, yes, it's getting this.

00:59:53.360 --> 00:59:54.820
Like in my experience, you need it

00:59:55.400 --> 00:59:56.780
whenever you talk to external systems

00:59:56.920 --> 00:59:58.500
because if you're doing this API cost,

00:59:58.660 --> 00:59:59.820
it will fail at some point.

01:00:00.020 --> 01:00:01.260
Just put it on it.

01:00:03.580 --> 01:00:05.140
Nowadays, it has a lot of more features.

01:00:05.320 --> 01:00:08.280
You can now have a callable that decides

01:00:08.560 --> 01:00:10.080
where you really want to retry.

01:00:10.100 --> 01:00:11.600
For example, you get an HTTP error,

01:00:11.760 --> 01:00:14.740
But in HTTPX, there's no difference between HTTP error

01:00:15.600 --> 01:00:19.020
because you got a 500 back or because you got a 401 back.

01:00:19.880 --> 01:00:22.260
If you keep retrying on 401 or 403,

01:00:22.480 --> 01:00:24.060
you will get banned from the API, right?

01:00:24.560 --> 01:00:27.320
But on a 500, you probably want to retry.

01:00:27.500 --> 01:00:28.120
These kind of things.

01:00:28.740 --> 01:00:29.060
Yeah.

01:00:30.500 --> 01:00:30.880
Yeah, absolutely.

01:00:33.080 --> 01:00:34.300
Yeah, the whole rate limiting thing,

01:00:34.420 --> 01:00:36.960
that's also tricky to work with.

01:00:36.960 --> 01:00:39.280
But I suppose if you said, OK, well, retry it,

01:00:39.420 --> 01:00:43.060
but put some kind of delay, maybe it'll be all right.

01:00:43.320 --> 01:00:44.420
The delay is built in.

01:00:44.920 --> 01:00:45.400
That's the whole point.

01:00:45.540 --> 01:00:46.640
It's exponential back off.

01:00:47.620 --> 01:00:48.140
Yeah, perfect.

01:00:49.440 --> 01:00:53.120
One thing I do want to talk about as well is just Argon.

01:00:53.960 --> 01:00:54.020
Yes.

01:00:54.020 --> 01:00:54.400
So quick.

01:00:56.860 --> 01:00:58.260
Very cool algorithm.

01:01:00.120 --> 01:01:03.940
It's one of these so-called memory hard problems

01:01:05.239 --> 01:01:07.820
that is somewhat resistant to brute forcing

01:01:08.110 --> 01:01:10.760
over just massive parallelism and so on.

01:01:11.520 --> 01:01:12.440
Want to talk about that real quick?

01:01:13.980 --> 01:01:14.120
Sure.

01:01:14.960 --> 01:01:15.500
What do you want to hear?

01:01:17.160 --> 01:01:18.460
Well, just tell people what it is.

01:01:18.580 --> 01:01:20.000
Maybe, you know, what's your project about

01:01:20.030 --> 01:01:22.720
and what should people consider using it, you know?

01:01:23.100 --> 01:01:24.660
Yeah, so many, many years ago,

01:01:25.420 --> 01:01:26.900
I think it was like 2016 or so,

01:01:27.020 --> 01:01:28.680
there was this password hashing competition

01:01:28.900 --> 01:01:33.120
because we needed to find a way to hash our passwords

01:01:33.120 --> 01:01:36.240
in a way that is, as you just said, memory hard.

01:01:36.900 --> 01:01:39.560
Right, if you hear of rainbow tables,

01:01:40.220 --> 01:01:41.740
you shouldn't be using MD5,

01:01:42.030 --> 01:01:43.760
all these things are all part of that.

01:01:44.020 --> 01:01:45.080
We've got to get past that, right?

01:01:45.620 --> 01:01:47.100
Yeah, so this is next level

01:01:47.170 --> 01:01:48.640
because people were running ASICs,

01:01:48.900 --> 01:01:51.100
so programmable boards

01:01:51.230 --> 01:01:55.040
that are just specifically for cracking passwords in parallel.

01:01:56.080 --> 01:02:00.080
The only way to fight this is make it memory hard.

01:02:00.120 --> 01:02:04.160
So like checking these passwords or this hashing algorithm

01:02:04.390 --> 01:02:06.980
also needs a lot of memory to work.

01:02:09.900 --> 01:02:13.280
There's one more famous one, which is called

01:02:13.830 --> 01:02:17.000
S-crypt or Yes-crypt, which is now it is also part of the standard library.

01:02:17.340 --> 01:02:18.740
So that's that.

01:02:18.740 --> 01:02:21.440
But Argon2 won the password hashing competition.

01:02:22.600 --> 01:02:25.220
And yeah, it works.

01:02:25.780 --> 01:02:27.620
It's in wide use.

01:02:27.900 --> 01:02:31.040
and yeah, I'm maintaining it for now like six years or something.

01:02:31.320 --> 01:02:32.200
Or I think longer.

01:02:33.100 --> 01:02:34.860
So if you're storing your own passwords,

01:02:35.680 --> 01:02:38.400
certainly this is one of the good options.

01:02:39.100 --> 01:02:43.260
Do you know what the story is with, oh gosh, what is it?

01:02:44.060 --> 01:02:45.100
Is it passlib, I believe?

01:02:46.440 --> 01:02:47.240
Oh, passlib.

01:02:47.300 --> 01:02:50.320
Oh man, this is, yeah, this is really, man.

01:02:51.120 --> 01:02:55.200
Passlib is throwing a lot of warnings about things that it's using

01:02:55.460 --> 01:02:57.640
that are being deprecated or even removed.

01:02:58.220 --> 01:03:04.760
I feel like it was really great for a while, but now if you go to it, it's like...

01:03:06.360 --> 01:03:08.520
Yeah, last edited four years ago, that's a problem.

01:03:08.700 --> 01:03:10.040
Yeah, it's not great.

01:03:10.600 --> 01:03:16.080
I feel like it was almost on SourceForge or something for a while, which is really...

01:03:16.460 --> 01:03:17.840
I can't remember exactly where I saw it.

01:03:17.900 --> 01:03:18.080
Bitbucket.

01:03:19.640 --> 01:03:20.240
Bitbucket is fine.

01:03:20.380 --> 01:03:21.280
Bitbucket is fine.

01:03:21.520 --> 01:03:21.780
Bitbucket is fine.

01:03:21.780 --> 01:03:22.120
No, it's not.

01:03:22.540 --> 01:03:23.140
It's gone.

01:03:24.120 --> 01:03:27.620
Oh, is Bitbucket

01:03:27.640 --> 01:03:32.580
the URL, this is Heptapod, which is the only Mercurial hosting

01:03:33.160 --> 01:03:36.580
that open source projects can use nowadays.

01:03:36.940 --> 01:03:37.080
Yeah.

01:03:38.200 --> 01:03:38.780
There you go.

01:03:38.920 --> 01:03:40.520
Bitbucket, you're getting Mercurial support, yeah.

01:03:40.920 --> 01:03:41.460
I see.

01:03:41.640 --> 01:03:42.160
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:03:42.760 --> 01:03:45.700
But will they also have Argon2 support, which is--

01:03:45.920 --> 01:03:46.880
Oh, they use my library.

01:03:47.600 --> 01:03:48.540
Yeah, that's what I thought.

01:03:48.660 --> 01:03:49.360
Yeah, that's what I thought.

01:03:50.020 --> 01:03:50.960
Yeah, super cool.

01:03:52.280 --> 01:03:52.400
Awesome.

01:03:52.800 --> 01:03:53.000
All right.

01:03:53.640 --> 01:03:57.620
Well, let's close this out with one more take

01:03:58.060 --> 01:04:01.020
I think we're pretty much out of time, but it's been a lot of fun.

01:04:02.480 --> 01:04:02.880
LLMs.

01:04:04.420 --> 01:04:05.820
LLMs writing code for us.

01:04:06.800 --> 01:04:09.580
Are we just going to be out of work in a year or two?

01:04:10.340 --> 01:04:11.240
What do you think about this?

01:04:11.300 --> 01:04:14.860
I'm not super worried about it, but it's definitely changing things, I think.

01:04:14.980 --> 01:04:20.060
When you say we, it can mean we, the two of us, and the answer is clearly no.

01:04:20.630 --> 01:04:24.920
I think we, as in Michael and Hinnick, will benefit from LLMs, I think.

01:04:26.580 --> 01:04:33.780
And we as programmers in general, and especially junior programmers, that's going to be a different

01:04:33.890 --> 01:04:34.060
thing.

01:04:34.070 --> 01:04:39.840
And I wouldn't dare to guess how that will play out.

01:04:41.259 --> 01:04:43.940
I'm personally using LLMs.

01:04:44.250 --> 01:04:45.660
I use Anthropic.

01:04:47.260 --> 01:04:55.260
But I use it in a way that I feel like you have to be very senior to actually use that.

01:04:55.800 --> 01:05:04.240
Because when you ask it for code, you just get code with old libraries because it's trained on old code from GitHub, right?

01:05:05.340 --> 01:05:10.060
Copilot once gave me SQL injection code.

01:05:11.780 --> 01:05:12.440
It'll be fine.

01:05:13.180 --> 01:05:18.820
I mean, what is the most common security problem with code?

01:05:18.820 --> 01:05:19.600
Yeah, SQL injections.

01:05:19.920 --> 01:05:23.260
Of course, it's going to be in those LLMs and suggesting it to me.

01:05:27.780 --> 01:05:30.740
So I think it is a useful tool.

01:05:31.620 --> 01:05:34.260
It usually doesn't give me what I need,

01:05:34.370 --> 01:05:38.240
but it gives me enough to help me to ask a search engine

01:05:38.510 --> 01:05:39.440
what I actually need.

01:05:40.820 --> 01:05:41.960
So that's what I'm going to say.

01:05:43.140 --> 01:05:45.540
What it's actually really good for is writing SQL,

01:05:45.770 --> 01:05:47.480
in my experience, because my brain,

01:05:47.510 --> 01:05:49.740
I somehow cannot write CTEs.

01:05:51.980 --> 01:05:53.460
The syntax, I don't know.

01:05:53.460 --> 01:05:54.180
I just can't.

01:05:54.300 --> 01:05:58.040
So I usually ask an LLM to write the CTE for me

01:05:58.040 --> 01:05:59.520
and then just write the rest of the query.

01:06:01.520 --> 01:06:02.820
Well, for me, that's regular expressions.

01:06:04.660 --> 01:06:05.560
That's why I go to LLMs.

01:06:05.560 --> 01:06:07.640
I'm like, you need to write me a regular expression

01:06:07.720 --> 01:06:11.020
with some capture groups because this is too much for me.

01:06:11.800 --> 01:06:13.940
JQ is also a good example for LLMs.

01:06:15.140 --> 01:06:15.340
Yeah.

01:06:16.560 --> 01:06:21.900
I've been using LM Studio, which is really nice.

01:06:22.180 --> 01:06:24.260
It lets you download a bunch of different models

01:06:25.280 --> 01:06:29.300
I've been running Lama and Mistral lately, and they've both been pretty good.

01:06:30.860 --> 01:06:31.960
Yeah, but they run locally, right?

01:06:32.110 --> 01:06:33.740
They run, it's free, it's super nice.

01:06:34.920 --> 01:06:39.400
So one thing that's pretty interesting here is if you talked about this as well,

01:06:39.400 --> 01:06:41.340
and I don't know what this trend means,

01:06:42.070 --> 01:06:45.060
but if you go to Stack Overflow Trends and you look at the most popular languages

01:06:46.150 --> 01:06:51.800
and you look right around late 2022, early 2023,

01:06:52.680 --> 01:06:57.660
There is a ridiculous drop in the popularity of questions

01:06:57.770 --> 01:07:01.720
on Stack Overflow for Python, for JavaScript,

01:07:02.680 --> 01:07:04.220
and interestingly not a whole lot for the others.

01:07:05.260 --> 01:07:08.140
But that's when ChatGPT came out.

01:07:10.620 --> 01:07:11.860
So I don't know what it's going to mean,

01:07:11.980 --> 01:07:14.540
but it's clearly having some kind of effect somewhere.

01:07:15.760 --> 01:07:17.700
But that might just be making people more productive

01:07:17.810 --> 01:07:19.040
and they're not on Stack Overflow.

01:07:19.270 --> 01:07:20.580
That might be a Stack Overflow problem.

01:07:20.680 --> 01:07:23.640
and not a development ecosystem problem.

01:07:24.580 --> 01:07:28.280
The friction to ask LLM is much smaller

01:07:28.330 --> 01:07:29.900
than asking actual people

01:07:30.150 --> 01:07:36.580
and then get trolled by some moderator or whatever.

01:07:37.520 --> 01:07:41.120
So I can see that people are going to prefer LLMs

01:07:41.150 --> 01:07:42.060
to talking to people.

01:07:42.110 --> 01:07:44.240
And also most questions on Stack Overflow

01:07:44.360 --> 01:07:45.660
are quite trivial, to be honest.

01:07:45.940 --> 01:07:47.020
So I think that makes sense.

01:07:48.960 --> 01:07:50.580
How do I connect to a database?

01:07:50.660 --> 01:07:51.720
is used in this library, right?

01:07:51.940 --> 01:07:52.560
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:07:52.840 --> 01:07:56.640
Or how do I disable SSL because I'm getting this certificate

01:07:56.880 --> 01:07:58.420
error all the time, the classics.

01:08:01.520 --> 01:08:03.680
But it also means that a lot of trash code

01:08:03.720 --> 01:08:04.920
is being written right now, right?

01:08:04.960 --> 01:08:06.060
Like the things that I just told you,

01:08:06.180 --> 01:08:08.540
that where you and I, we look at this code

01:08:08.540 --> 01:08:11.080
and we say, OK, this in principle is useful,

01:08:11.940 --> 01:08:13.480
but I cannot put this into production

01:08:13.620 --> 01:08:16.839
because error handling is wrong or there's

01:08:17.100 --> 01:08:18.400
some security issue or whatever.

01:08:19.680 --> 01:08:21.600
This is something that actually concerns me.

01:08:23.600 --> 01:08:25.520
A lot of people are writing code they don't understand

01:08:25.700 --> 01:08:26.600
and putting into production,

01:08:26.799 --> 01:08:29.359
and I think that's going to have consequences

01:08:29.680 --> 01:08:30.700
that are not going to be pretty.

01:08:31.340 --> 01:08:32.920
Yeah, I totally agree with you.

01:08:32.920 --> 01:08:35.880
And also one of my concerns, and you touched on as well,

01:08:35.920 --> 01:08:38.839
is how do you go from beginning developer

01:08:40.540 --> 01:08:42.700
to slightly beyond junior developer?

01:08:45.620 --> 01:08:46.900
I don't know if LLMs are going to help people

01:08:46.980 --> 01:08:47.839
make that jump quicker,

01:08:48.400 --> 01:08:56.180
Or if they're just going to make that jump like a wider chasm because people won't need juniors because they're just going to ask the LLM to just do the thing, you know?

01:08:58.000 --> 01:08:58.440
Yeah, yeah.

01:08:58.460 --> 01:08:59.400
This is the problem.

01:09:02.259 --> 01:09:07.680
Like bean counters are going to look into Excel and I got to wonder what makes more sense, right?

01:09:08.279 --> 01:09:16.380
And the fact they're eating their seed for next year and there's suddenly, oh my God, why are there no new senior software engineers?

01:09:16.900 --> 01:09:18.060
Well, we didn't make them.

01:09:19.040 --> 01:09:20.580
It's going to be like Cobalt.

01:09:21.490 --> 01:09:24.759
There'll be fewer people who are really, really needed

01:09:24.920 --> 01:09:25.620
to keep things working.

01:09:26.130 --> 01:09:27.299
We will never retire, Michael.

01:09:28.029 --> 01:09:28.140
Exactly.

01:09:29.340 --> 01:09:30.960
We're going to be programming on the beach

01:09:31.080 --> 01:09:32.960
with our margaritas in our 70s.

01:09:34.480 --> 01:09:35.660
Well, let's leave it there.

01:09:36.160 --> 01:09:36.859
Is that a positive take?

01:09:36.940 --> 01:09:37.160
I don't know.

01:09:37.170 --> 01:09:38.720
I really enjoyed our conversation, though.

01:09:39.580 --> 01:09:41.140
And a lot of good advice for people.

01:09:41.380 --> 01:09:42.400
So thanks for being here.

